In the photoexcitation process, an incident photon, whose energy is equal to or higher than the bandgap energy (Eg) of the targeted materials, imparts its energy to the valence band electron of the photoabsorber material and excites it to the higher energy level (conduction band). The excited electrons in the conduction band leave a positive charge behind in the valance band, termed as an excited hole. These excited species are collectively called “excitons” or “free charge carriers”. However, if the excitation energy is far higher than Eg, the charge carriers jump to even higher energy states, termed as energy sub-bands, which are above the conduction band minimum (CBM) and below the valence band maximum (VBM) for excited electrons and excited holes, respectively. The highly excited charge carriers are hot electrons and hot holes, collectively termed as HC, as shown in Fig. 4 (see ref. 21). HC convert their excess energy to heat upon de-excitation. The distribution of the excess energy between the HC is described by the following equations22:1ΔEe=(hν−Eg)1+me*mh*−1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
