The basic operation of a HC solar cell is to utilize the temperature gradient established between the HC (TC) and the lattice (TL) to get higher voltages than are otherwise obtainable in a conventional PV cell4. ESCs extract HC with specific energies (Ee for hot electrons and Ep for hot holes) with an energy window of δE from the absorber. The bandwidth of the energy selective window (ESW) has to be narrow, less than kBTL, in order to prevent the HC from relaxing to the lower states and cooling down isentropically to TL. The open-circuit voltage of the device is given by Eq. (4),8eVOC=μehc=ΔEeh1−TLTeh+ΔμTLTeh\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
